export const HOME_FAQS = [
  { q: "What insurance does a hotshot trucker need?", a: "A working hotshot operation typically needs primary trucking liability (FMCSA-mandated), motor truck cargo, physical damage on the truck and trailer, bobtail or non-trucking liability, occupational accident or workers' comp, general liability, and often commercial umbrella. Most owner-operators carry the full stack as one coordinated program to satisfy brokers and protect the business." },
  { q: "How much does hotshot insurance cost?", a: "It depends on your truck and trailer value, your cargo limits, your authority status (your own MC vs. leased), your radius, CDL status, what you haul, and your loss history. A leased operator may pay several thousand a year; an independent running their own authority with $100K+ cargo and a long-haul radius runs considerably more. We quote your actual operation in about 15 minutes — never a generic estimate." },
  { q: "Do I need my own MC/USDOT authority to get hotshot insurance?", a: "No — you can insure a leased owner-operator who runs under a carrier's authority. But if you operate interstate under your own MC authority, FMCSA requires primary liability (typically $750K–$1M) and cargo coverage to be filed before your authority goes active. We structure programs for both leased and independent operators." },
  { q: "What's the FMCSA minimum insurance for hotshot trucking?", a: "For most interstate freight authority, FMCSA requires $750,000 in primary liability (commonly written at $1,000,000), plus cargo coverage filed on form BMC-91X or BMC-34. Hazardous materials and certain high-value or passenger exposures require higher limits. We confirm exactly what your authority and your freight require." },
  { q: "Do I need a CDL to get hotshot insurance?", a: "No. Many hotshot operators run non-CDL with a Class 3–5 pickup (F-350/450/550, Ram, GM HD) under 26,000 lbs GVWR combined, and we insure non-CDL operations every day. CDL status affects pricing and some carriers' appetite, but it is not a requirement to obtain coverage." },
  { q: "What does motor truck cargo insurance cover?", a: "Cargo covers the freight in your care, custody, and control — damage, loss, theft, and sometimes reefer or contamination exposure depending on the load. It pays the shipper or broker when the load doesn't arrive in the condition it was tendered. Most brokers require $100K minimum and oilfield or high-value loads often require more." },
  { q: "How much cargo insurance do I need for hotshot trucking?", a: "Most brokers and load boards require a $100,000 cargo minimum. Oilfield pipe and equipment, machinery, steel, and high-value freight often require $150K–$300K or more. We size cargo to the freight you actually haul and the shippers you want to work with — a default number that's too low gets you turned down for the loads you want." },
  { q: "What's the difference between bobtail and non-trucking liability?", a: "Bobtail covers you driving the truck without a trailer attached (bobtailing) after a load is delivered, typically under a leased-operator arrangement. Non-trucking liability (NTL) is broader — covering personal, non-revenue use of the truck outside dispatched business. Both fill the gap primary liability leaves when you're not under a load." },
  { q: "Do I need bobtail insurance if I have primary liability?", a: "Often yes. Primary trucking liability covers you while operating under a load or in dispatched service. When you deadhead, bobtail, or drive the truck for personal use, primary may not respond. Bobtail and non-trucking liability fill that gap — and many lease agreements require them." },
  { q: "Does physical damage cover my truck and trailer?", a: "Physical damage is collision plus comprehensive on your owned truck and trailer. It pays to repair or replace your rig after a crash, theft, fire, vandalism, storm, or rollover. If you're financed, we add gap coverage so a totaled rig doesn't leave you owing more than it's worth." },
  { q: "What is occupational accident insurance and do I need it?", a: "Occupational accident (occ-acc) covers accidental death, dismemberment, and medical and disability benefits if you're injured on the job — it's an owner-operator's alternative to workers' comp. Most carriers require leased operators to carry it (or workers' comp), and it's often the most cost-effective injury coverage for an independent." },
  { q: "Occupational accident vs. workers' comp for hotshot — which do I need?", a: "Workers' comp is statutory coverage for employees and is often required if you have W-2 drivers. Occupational accident is the contractor-friendly alternative most leased owner-operators carry for themselves. If you're independent with no employees, occ-acc is typically the right fit; if you have employees, workers' comp is usually required. We help you choose." },
  { q: "Do I need general liability if I already have auto liability?", a: "Usually yes. Auto liability covers vehicle-related accidents. Motor truck general liability covers the rest — bodily injury and property damage while loading and unloading, at a shipper's lot, or from your operation off the roadway. Most brokers and oilfield accounts require GL on top of auto liability." },
  { q: "Why is hotshot insurance so expensive?", a: "Because a loaded hotshot rig carries serious third-party and cargo exposure — a single at-fault wreck with a loaded trailer can produce a seven-figure claim. Cost is driven by your authority, cargo limits, radius, truck/trailer value, driving record, and loss history. The right markets and a clean record materially lower the number; we shop aggressively to get you the best rate." },
  { q: "Do you write hotshot insurance in all 50 states?", a: "Yes. Contractors Choice Agency is licensed in all 50 states and has markets for hotshot owner-operators whether you run out of the Permian, the Bakken, the Gulf Coast, the Midwest, or anywhere in between." },
  { q: "How fast can we get a hotshot insurance quote?", a: "Typically 15 minutes on a call. For operators with a new MC authority, prior losses, or high cargo minimums we may need a day or two to involve the right markets, but we move fast and tell you the timeline up front — authority filings often can't wait." },
  { q: "Will you insure a hotshot operator who's been declined or has prior losses?", a: "Often yes. We have admitted and excess-and-surplus (E&S) trucking markets for operators declined over a prior at-fault, oilfield cargo exposure, a new MC authority, or other issues. Bring us what you have and we'll find a path." },
  { q: "Do you provide certificates of insurance for brokers and shippers?", a: "Yes — fast. We issue certificates naming brokers, shippers, and oilfield accounts as certificate holders or additional insureds, often same-day, so you don't lose a load waiting on paperwork." },
  { q: "Should I bundle all my hotshot coverage with one program?", a: "Usually yes. Bundling primary liability, cargo, physical damage, bobtail, occupational accident, and GL into one coordinated program closes gaps between policies and is almost always cheaper and cleaner than separate policies from separate carriers — and far easier to manage at claim time." },
  { q: "What is trailer interchange insurance and do I need it?", a: "Trailer interchange covers physical damage to non-owned trailers you pull under a trailer-interchange or power-only agreement. If you pull shipper- or carrier-owned trailers and damage or lose one, interchange pays to repair or replace it. Standard physical damage excludes non-owned trailers, so if you run power-only or interchange, you need it." },
];

